bioghist.head: Biographical Sketch
bioghist.p: The invertebrate holdings at Yale University now in the Yale Peabody Museum's Division of Invertebrate Zoology began to grow immediately with the arrival of Addison E. Verrill in 1864 as the University?s first Professor of Zoology. Named Curator of Zoology in 1866 at the newly founded Peabody Museum, his collecting and describing of local marine and freshwater fauna formed the basis of what was to evolve into a major collection of Western Atlantic coastal invertebrates for the Museum.

The study of Atlantic Coast invertebrates obtained through Verrill's 16-year association with the U.S. Fish Commission (including examples of rare deepwater forms taken by the steamers Speedwell, Fish Hawk and Albatross) resulted in the discovery of many new species, some described by Verrill's students and assistants: Oscar Harger (isopods); Katherine J. Bush (mollusks); and Verrill's brother-in-law and fellow Yale professor, Sidney I. Smith (crustaceans). Verrill and Smith's Invertebrate Animals of Vineyard Sound (1873) remains an important reference manual of Atlantic Coast marine invertebrate fauna.

Verrill also actively secured material from various collectors (notably F.H. Bradley and J.A. McNiel), including corals, shells and echinoderms from the Gulf of California, Central and South America, and maintained exchange programs with Harvard University's Museum of Comparative Zoology, the Smithsonian Institution, the Essex Institute, the Boston Society of Natural History, and other institutions. Both Verrill and Smith (who worked exclusively on crustaceans) described many new taxa from this exchanged material. Corals were of particular interest to Verrill; he published extensively on the Peabody specimens, including a review of coral type specimens originally described by James D. Dana from material collected by the United States Exploring Expedition (1836?1842).

A huge collection of invertebrates from expeditions to Bermuda in 1898 and 1901 formed the basis of many of Verrill's articles and monographs. Other specialists enlisted to describe the Bermudan fauna included, among others, W.G. Van Name (tunicates), Harriet Richardson (isopods), Beverley W. Kunkel (amphipods) and Katherine Bush (polychaetes).
After Verrill's retirement in 1910, the growth of the Museum's invertebrate collections slowed considerably, although he continued to publish until his death in 1926.

Verrill's student Wesley R. Coe, a nemertean specialist, followed Verrill as curator in 1911. Earlier, as a member of the Harriman Alaska Expedition (1899), Coe had obtained for Yale the nemerteans and tube dwelling polychaetes (sabellid and serpulid) that he and Katherine Bush described in important monographs. Stanley C. Ball succeeded Coe as the Peabody's Curator of Zoology, serving until 1954. In 1953, Willard D. Hartman began a nearly 40-year tenure as the Museum's first Curator of Invertebrate Zoology, serving until his retirement in 1992. Under his stewardship the collections began to grow again, particularly in areas of his principle research interest, the systematics and evolution of sponges and their association with coral reefs. Hartman assembled a large series of invertebrates, primarily sponges and corals, from many Caribbean localities and was a participant in several expeditions to the tropics, notably to the Indian Ocean (Yale Seychelles Expedition, 1957?1958), Jamaica and Belize (NEKTON submersible dives, 1972), and the Philippines (ALPHA HELIX cruise, 1975). Many of Hartman's students conducted research on sponges and corals, particularly from the Caribbean, and the Pacific coast of Panama, have resulted in large collections of these organisms at the Yale Peabody Museum.
In 1959 divisional holdings increased greatly with the incorporation of invertebrate specimens from Yale's Bingham Oceanographic Collection.

scopecontent.head: Description of the Material
scopecontent.p: These are the miscellaneous archives associated with the Division of the Invertebrate Zoology and previously (until 1953-1954) the Division of Zoology, including ledgers, correspondence, annual reports, etc.

did.unittitle: Aquisitions. Archives related to the Divisional Aquisitions.
Aquisitions. A list of bird eggs apparently sent to Yale College from the Smithsonian. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquisitions. A list of Insects donated to the collection during 1866.
Aquisitions. A reprint of a T.H. Bean (1880) publication. See bibliography record IZ.11632. Numerous UNSM numbers are checked off, presumably duplicates of those specimens are in the Museum.

Aquisitions. A letter and specimen list from G.B. Goode to A.E. Verrill informing him of specimens sent to the YPM from the USNM. They include ocean bottom samples, Crinoidea, Ateroidea and collection of dupilcate deep sea fishes. The Crinoidea and fish were sent in exchange for the valuable services Verrill had rendered for the Museum. The ocean bottom samples and Asteroidea were sent for study on J.E. Benedict's recommendation. There is a list of the deep-sea fishes, received in good order by A.E. Verrill, 15 Dec 1894.

Aquisitions. A letter sent to A.E. Verrill via Prof. William Beebe in regards to Lepidoptera and other Insects collected around Eagle City, Alaska by Plato Mountjoy collected from Jul 1900 to 16 Aug 1900. The letter is describing the collection, apparently sent to Verrill.
Aquisitions. A list of Crustacea received from the Smithsonian. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquisitions. A list of bird species and lot counts. Possibly an aquisition.

Aquisitions. A list of fishes received from the MCZ. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquisitions. A list of Butterflies from Norway, ME. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquisitions. A list of Mammals, possible received from the Smithsonian. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquisitions. A list of invertebrates (Cephaolopoa, Echinodermata, etc.) from Thomas A Streets of the U.S. Stmr. Portsmouth. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquistions. A list of bird eggs sent to Yale College from the Smithsonian. Printed numbers are USNM catalog numbers. See Invoice Ledger.
Aquistions. A list of coral specimens given to A.E. Verrill from the Essex Institue for services in identifying their collections. See Invoice Ledger.
Correspondence. Correspondence relating to Divisional aquisitions, loans and exchanges.
Corresdpondence. A letter from Dr. Vaughn, McGill University, Montreal Canada, to C.E. Bush, acknowledging the receipt of specimens forwarded by her.

Correspondence. 2 letters. A letter from A.E. Verrill to Office of Tice & Lynch Custom House Brokers protesting the payment of $7.40 for the storage os specimens. A return letter From Tice & Lynch acknowledging the receipt of payment and apologizing for the necessary bill.

Exchanges. 2 lists of spiders, one list to be sent to J.H. Emerton and one to be sent to William Holden.
Exchanges. A list of Mollusca sent to P.P. Carpenter, some to be retained by Carpenter. Probably in exchange. See Invoice Ledger.
Exchanges. List of Lithobiidae (centipedes) sent to Anton Stuxberg. The genera include Lithobius and Bothropolys.
Exchanges. A list of Mollusca possibly related to an exchange with C.F. Lutken. See Invoice Ledger.
Exchanges. A list of brids and bird eggs received in exchange from the Chicago Academy of Sciences. Some of the specimens originated at the USNM. See Invoice Ledger,
Exchanges. A list of the Duplicates of American Echinoderms in Yale College Museum. Within the folded list is a list of Echinodermata for C.F. Lutken.
Exchanges. A list of Insects sent to the Essex Institute. Some in exchange.
Exchanges. List of sspecimens sent to C.C. Nutting in exchange. Mostly Hydrozoa.
Exchanges. A list of spiders sent to William Holden, presumably in exchange.
Exchanges. A list of Mollusca sent to P.P. Carpenter for identification. Some were to be retained by Carpenter, probably in exchange. See Invoice Ledger.

Exchanges. A letter from the Smithsonian Institute acknowledging the receipt of 5 specimens, Pocillopora frendosa, Pocillopora nobilis var. tuberosa, Coenopsammia tenuilamellosa, Montipora patula and Porites languinosa, in exchange. USNM Acc. No. 44293.
Exchanges. List of Echinodermata from the Essex Institute. Some were to be returned to the Essex Instutue. See Invoice Ledger.
Exchanges. A list of Specimens received from the Boston Society of Natural History in exchange. Mostly Cnidaria and Echinodermata. See Invoice Ledger.
Exchanges. A list of specimens requested from the Museum of Comparative Zoology by A.E. Verrill for Yale College. Appear to be all Anthozoa.
Exchanges. A list of Annulata from C.F. Lutken sent to the Museum in exchange.
Exchanges. A list of specimens (Anthozoa, Echinodermata) from the Essex Institute, most likely in exchange. Specimens have both and Essex Institute and YPM number. See Invoice Ledger.
Exchanges. A Catalog of Fossils sent to Mr. John Cummings, Jr.
Exchanges. A List of Duplicate Alyconaria in the Museum of Yale College which may be sold. A note at the top of the list in Verrill's hand reads "March 1869. Sent to British Museum."
Exchanges. VarioList of specimens sent to the USNM, most likely in exchange. Most appear to be Crustacea from Bermuda and Brazil.
Exchanges. A list of of specimens sent to the Boston Society of Natural History. Mostly Echinodermata and Anthozoa.
